-- Field Journal pen: Aino Karvonen (Seasons & Light desk). Summer 2026 batch.
insert into public.blog_posts (
  slug, title, kicker, excerpt, category_slug, tags, hero_image, hero_alt,
  content, author_id, author_snapshot, status, published_at, featured,
  read_time_minutes
) values (
  'the-sun-did-not-set-it-just-circled-the-house',
  'The sun did not set, it just circled the house',
  'Sodankylä · June · Nightless night',
  'A week above the Arctic Circle in June, in which the sun goes around the cabin like a slow moth around a lamp, the birds refuse to stop singing, and sleep becomes a matter of opinion.',
  'seasons',
  ARRAY['midnight-sun','sodankyla','summer','sleep']::text[],
  '/images/summer-midnight-sun-1200.webp',
  'Low golden midnight sun over a red wooden cabin and birch trees, long shadows across a meadow',
  '[{"type":"paragraph","text":"At twenty past one in the morning I went outside to check whether it was night. This is not a sentence that makes sense anywhere south of the Arctic Circle, and I want to be precise about what I mean. I did not go out to see the night. I went out to check whether night, as a concept, was being observed at all. It was not. The sun was sitting a hand-width above the treeline to the north, round and orange and completely unbothered, lighting the side of the cabin that the landlord had painted red sixty years ago, and a willow warbler was going through its entire repertoire at full volume as if it were nine in the morning."},{"type":"paragraph","text":"I was in a rented cabin a few kilometres outside Sodankylä for a week in the middle of June. Sodankylä sits at about sixty-seven degrees north, which means the sun stays above the horizon for roughly seven weeks in summer, from late May to the middle of July. Everyone knows this fact before they come. It is on every website. What the websites do not tell you is what the fact does to a human being who has spent forty years on a planet where evening is followed by darkness, and darkness by morning, in that order, reliably, as a kind of contract."},{"type":"heading","level":2,"text":"What the light actually does"},{"type":"paragraph","text":"The first thing to understand is that the midnight sun is not the midday sun at midnight. Between about eleven in the evening and three in the morning the light goes long and low and golden, the way it does in the last hour before sunset further south — except the sunset never arrives. The whole landscape sits inside that last golden hour for four hours. Shadows stretch out fifty metres and just stay there, pointing south, barely moving. The birches go copper. The lake steams a little. Photographers call the hour before sunset the golden hour, and they cross oceans to catch twenty minutes of it. Up here in June it is not an hour. It is a shift."},{"type":"paragraph","text":"The second thing is the birds. Somewhere around two in the morning of the first night I understood that the willow warbler outside my window was not confused. I was the one holding the wrong assumptions. The birds up here run on light, not on clocks, and the light said sing. They sing at a volume and persistence that no alarm clock manufacturer has dared to imitate, and they do not take requests."},{"type":"pullquote","text":"You do not watch the midnight sun. You stand inside it, slightly too awake, wondering what your body plans to do about all this."},{"type":"paragraph","text":"The third thing is what happens inside your own head. Around day three, time goes soft at the edges. You eat dinner at ten in the evening because the light says it is late afternoon. You find yourself sweeping the porch at half past midnight with genuine enthusiasm. You lie down at one, wide awake, and read forty pages. The Finnish word for the nightless night is yötön yö, and I had always thought of it as a tourist phrase, but by the middle of the week I had started to hear it as a plain description of a technical problem: there is no night, and the machinery in you that waits for night keeps waiting."},{"type":"heading","level":2,"text":"The foil, the mask, and other negotiations"},{"type":"paragraph","text":"The cabin had thin yellow curtains that glowed like a lampshade. On the second day I did the thing that every northern local does and every visitor eventually discovers: I taped a rescue blanket over the bedroom window, silver side out. It looked terrible. It worked completely. The room went a deep honest grey, and my body, offered this small forgery of night, accepted it without asking questions."},{"type":"paragraph","text":"A sleep mask does most of the same work and travels better. I had one in my bag and ended up wearing it every night, under protest, because sleep masks make me feel like a person in an advertisement for long-haul flights. Under the mask and behind the foil I slept seven hours a night for the rest of the week. The people I later spoke to in the village were divided into two camps: those who black out their bedrooms with the seriousness of a photographic darkroom, and those who claim they sleep fine in full daylight and have simply stopped negotiating. Both camps drink a lot of coffee."},{"type":"paragraph","text":"What nobody in either camp does is fight the light in the evening. The evenings are the point. Between ten and one the village empties out onto lakeshores and porches and boat docks. People mow lawns, burn brush, fish, sit. There is a particular unhurried quality to a conversation held at eleven in the evening in full sunshine with no closing time anywhere on the horizon. Nobody looks at a watch. The light has already answered the only question a watch can ask."},{"type":"image","src":"/images/summer-midnight-sun-1200.webp","alt":"Low golden midnight sun over a red wooden cabin and birch trees, long shadows across a meadow","caption":"Twenty past one in the morning, facing north. The sun does not go down. It goes sideways.","full":true},{"type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Notes for anyone coming north in June"},{"type":"list","items":["Bring a sleep mask even if you hate them. You can decide on the first night whether you are a foil-on-the-window person, but the mask buys you that first night.","Do not schedule anything important before ten in the morning. Your rhythm will drift late, everyone else has also drifted late, and the village runs on a quiet agreement about this.","The best light is between eleven in the evening and two in the morning. If you photograph, plan around that window and sleep afterwards, not before.","Eat at normal hours even when the light argues otherwise. Meals are the one clock your body still believes.","If you wake at three in the morning wide awake, go outside for ten minutes instead of fighting it in bed. The world at three is worth seeing, and the tiredness arrives properly once you have seen it.","Warm layers matter at night even in June. The sun stays up, but the temperature still drops, and sitting on a dock at one in the morning in a T-shirt is a mistake you make once."]},{"type":"heading","level":2,"text":"The last morning"},{"type":"paragraph","text":"On the last morning I took the foil off the window and folded it into my bag, because a rescue blanket that has done a week of honest work deserves better than the bin. The room filled with light instantly, the way a bucket fills when you take the lid off a well. Outside, the warbler was already going, or still going. I never established which."},{"type":"paragraph","text":"I drove south after breakfast, and somewhere around Ranua, for the first time in a week, the evening began to look like an evening — the light thickening, the shadows joining up, a proper dusk assembling itself over the road. I noticed that I felt two things at once: relief, because my body recognised the old contract coming back into force, and a small unreasonable grief, because for one week the day had simply refused to end, and there is a version of you that starts to believe it never has to."},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"paragraph","text":"Written from Sodankylä in the third week of June, between two in the morning and three, with the window open and the sun to the north."}]'::jsonb,
  NULL,
  '{"handle":"aino","display_name":"Aino Karvonen","avatar_url":null}'::jsonb,
  'published',
  '2026-06-14'::timestamptz,
  false,
  8
)
